      <h2>How to Choose Based on Your Work</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Residential Service Electrician:</strong> Fluke 117/323 Kit. Covers every diagnostic scenario from panel to receptacle. The non-contact voltage detector alone saves time on every call.</li>
        <li><strong>Commercial Electrician:</strong> Milwaukee 2236-20 or Klein 69149P. If you're on M18, the Milwaukee keeps battery commonality. If you want a broader kit, Klein's bundle includes an outlet tester and NCVT.</li>
        <li><strong>HVAC / Refrigeration Tech:</strong> Milwaukee 2236-20 for amp draw checks on compressors and blowers, plus temperature probe compatibility.</li>
        <li><strong>Industrial / Controls Technician:</strong> 6000-count DMM for its finer resolution on 4-20 mA loops, thermocouples, and low-resistance windings.</li>
        <li><strong>Apprentice / Student:</strong> AstroAI DMM for basic learning. Upgrade to a Fluke or Klein once you're working live panels regularly.</li>
        <li><strong>Truck Spare / Loaner:</strong> AstroAI Clamp Meter. Cheap enough to replace, capable enough for quick checks.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Final Verdict</h2>
      <p>If you can only buy one test tool for professional electrical work, the <strong>Fluke 117/323 Kit</strong> (4.8 stars) is the answer. It's the most recommended meter among master electricians for a reason — it's safe, accurate, and the 117's VoltAlert feature pays for itself in time saved on the first big troubleshooting call.</p>
      <p>If the Fluke is out of budget, the <strong>Klein 69149P</strong> delivers comparable capability with a broader accessory bundle at a lower entry price. And if you're ecosystem-committed to Milwaukee, the <strong>2236-20 clamp meter</strong> is a rugged, job-site-proven alternative that doesn't compromise on safety ratings.</p>

